{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513434","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513434"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:09:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:09:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12109"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12109"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.14,0.18,0.65,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4653"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61429"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4653"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12109"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46880"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"112"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7090"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7103"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19601"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40615"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61429"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man presents to the clinic with three months of increasing back pain. He localises the pain to the lumbar spine and states that the pain is worst at night while he is lying in bed. It is improved during the day with mobilisation. His medical history is notable only for hypertension for which he takes perindopril. He has a 20 pack-year smoking history, but ceased about 15 years ago. A complete physical examination is unremarkable. His laboratory studies are notable for a raised alkaline phosphatase. An X-ray of the spine is performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastric carcinoma","Non-small cell lung cancer","Osteosarcoma","Carcinoma of the prostate","Thyroid carcinoma"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe X-ray shows areas of increased bone density in the lumbar spine and pelvis (Image).\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003EThese are sclerotic metastatic deposits. Lung\u003Cstrong\u003E, \u003C/strong\u003Ebreast and \u003Cstrong\u003Eprostate\u003C/strong\u003E cancers account for approximately 80% of bone metastases. It is well recognised that, with prostate cancer in particular, the first evidence of the disease can be symptoms related to bony metastases. Some 6% of patients with carcinoma of the prostate will present with symptoms of metastatic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other two mentioned cancers (gastric, thyroid) less frequently metastasise to bone. The spine is the most common site for bone metastases. Other common sites are the pelvis, upper femur, humerus, ribs, and the skull. Metastatic lesions may be lytic (less dense) or blastic (sclerotic and denser). Most cancers cause a combination of both, although prostate cancer is predominantly blastic. Whilst with his smoking history, the possibility of an underlying bronchogenic neoplasm must be considered, the bony deposits from this source are usually lytic. Osteosarcoma is a less common cause of bone cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEither blastic or lytic lesions may cause hypercalcaemia, although lytic lesions more commonly do this. Lytic lesions are best detected with plain radiography. Blastic lesions are prominent on radionuclide bone scans. In osteolytic bone metastases, the alkaline phosphatase enzyme is elevated secondary to a local bone formation response in an attempt to compensate for the predominant destructive lesion. In osteoblastic bone metastases, alkaline phosphatase is elevated secondary to local stimulation of osteoblasts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The bone is a common site for metastases, the primary sites most often being prostate, breast, and lung cancers."],"references":["Rossi A, Gridelli C, Ricciardi S, de Marinis F. Bone metastases and non-small cell lung cancer: from bisphosphonates to targeted therapy. Curr Med Chem. 2012;19(32):5524-35.","Rodriguez P, Khoshbin K, Vakil J, et al.  Metastatic Prostate Adenocarcinoma: A Rare Presentation. Cureus 2022; 14(1):e21292."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46880"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12109"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20022"},{"type":"media","id":"20023"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20834"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20022"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e5d30f7c-3a4a-4b5e-a9af-9ac86454f06d.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/e5d30f7c-3a4a-4b5e-a9af-9ac86454f06d.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":681,"height":828}},{"type":"media","id":"20023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20023"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0fc247a7-93ef-4047-986f-577ba93b1380.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0fc247a7-93ef-4047-986f-577ba93b1380.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":681,"height":828}},{"type":"media","id":"20834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20834"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/SwaeL3fbCpdgDOduOmN8bniikCnyW7.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/SwaeL3fbCpdgDOd